In the 60's when I talked about my opposition to the war I<br>
said that it was a war of National Liberation, of a people<br>
trying to overthrow a government that was dominated by an<br>
imperialist force (i.e. the U.S.A.) this is different from<br>
calling it a peasant uprising or civil war. It acknowledges<br>
the role of the US as the force controlling the South Viet-<br>
namese government. <br><br>
I think that the issue for me was one of the rights of<br>
nations to control their internal affairs. In an internal<br>
struggle, a nation has the right to control its own destiny<br>
whether or not we agree with the outcome or the methodology.<br><br>
At times it is difficult to &quot;sit on our hands&quot; and watch <br>
without interfering. While I state this position and am<br>
defending the supremacy of nationhood I also acknowledge that<br>
their are exceptions such as genocide that should force us<br>
to intervene. <br><br>
What we need to sort out is how to implement this in a global<br>
strategy that furthers mankind.,<br><br>
If we could teach this to our children then we would have a<br>
far better world than the one I grew up in.
